  <span id="freeText267741703311183146" style="display:none">At its most prosaic, Amadeus could be a play about American business, with Salieri in the role of the manager protecting his established position by blocking the professional advancement of the brilliant, young Mozart.<br />While accurate, that description is far too bloodless. <br />For Salieri is a transcendent villain, blending the seething jealousy of Iago, the monomaniacal passion of Ahab, and the arrogant defiance of Lucifer. His jealous rage burns too hot to be focused on a mere human, and his quest to destroy Mozart becomes a defiant challenge against God himself. <br />This is Salieri’s play, but Mozart creates its counterpoint. Gauche, boorish, and exuberant, the play’s Mozart explodes into every scene, adding humor and brightness to the sinister darkness spun by the antihero, Salieri. <br />The sublime music is a vital part of Amadeus. I recommend experiencing it through LA Theater Works excellent production of the play. </span>
