  <span id="freeText265042220769674304" style="display:none">After watching the National Theatre’s streaming production and being blown away by that revival, I needed to read the original play.<br /><br />The staged play is so reliant on music that reading <i>Amadeus</i> is akin coming to the story fresh. On page, the dialogue and wordplay take center stage, and the play is as phenomenal on page as it is on stage, if for different reasons. Although not even remotely historically accurate, Shaffer’s imagined relationship between Salieri and Mozart, especially Salieri’s jealousy and Mozart’s genius, works as a tale of the power of artistic genius.<br /><br />Reading it – and I apologize for this sacrilege – I was reminded of Peyton Manning once talking about how he and Tom Brady chatted regularly. For fans of American football, Manning and Brady are one of the sport’s greatest on-field rivalries. But listening to Manning talk, I realized: they are part of a very small club of ultra-elite athletes. Few people can grasp their commitment, the pressures of the job, or the deep love and understanding of the game.<br /><br />Shaffer captures that dynamic in <i>Amadeus</i>. Salieri both hates and loves Mozart’s talent as only another elite composer could. Absolutely captivating. Highly recommended.<br /><br />ETA: Huh. The 1980s film is unremarkable compared to the 2016 National Theatre revival. The film changes the wrong details and attempts to hew too closely to historic reality in a play that makes a merry mess of fact. </span>
